Here we have another unique sonnet. It looks as if
Shakespeare thought this was a good place in the book to
display his versatility. Alas, someone in the copying
process allowed in a careless blunder. The repetition of 'my
sinful earth' at the beginning of line 2 is unShakespearian
(he does  not repeat himself), it conveys no meaning and it
gives us four syllables where we need two. No doubt there
will be someone to defend it!

The emendation 'feeding' is attributed by Burrow to
'Sebastian Evans in Cambridge 1893', an edition of the Works
edited by W.A. Wright. It is powerfully supported by Helen
Vendler , who among much else refers to a comment by Walton
Litz that lines 1-2 generate line 9, lines 3-4 generate line
10, lines 5-6 generate line 11 and lines 7-8 generate line
12. The idea of feeding, and the word itself, pervade the
poem.

There is no difficulty in saying the transmitted text is
wrong, but with this kind of error, which obliterates all
trace of the original words, there can be no claim of
certainty for any emendation. Still, the case looks good to
me.

The fallen angels in line 2 would fit into Paradise Lost,
but the story is far older than Milton.

The advice in lines 9-12 seems very abstract and
metaphorical. I am not clear what is being prescribed.
Fasting and prayer? Giving to the poor?

--
Robert Stonehouse
