S146 Paraphrase.

-------
1. Poor soul, the center of my sinful, personal world,
2. {Renounce} these "rebel" forces that you've fielded!
(and must pay for)

The correct wording at the beginning of line 2 is unknown, due to a
misprint in the original.  I supply the word "renounce" because it
appears to express the intended sentiment, and it also has a
definition as a legal term -- the Poet was inclined to use common
words that were also legal terms.

I take the tone of the opening couplet to be imperative, or
adjuratory.  The Poet is "preaching" to his own soul.  The "rebel"
forces are the flesh and its associated desires, which desires are
selfish, easily leading the body into sin, contrary to what's good for
the soul.  The soul commands the body, in classical depiction, but the
body is also rebellious against the best interests of the soul,
because of the desires of the flesh -- this internal struggle is a
paradox of the human condition.

"Renounce", or any wording supplied at the start of line 2, is only a
reader's guess, nothing more.  The Poet did use "renounce" in his
plays some 5 times, including the following from King Lear, where the
word "world" also appears.  So, the Poet did place "renounce" near the
word "world" in this type of sentiment, at least in Lear.

-=-=-
King Lear
Act 4, Scene 6
Gloucester [Kneeling]  O you mighty gods!
This world I do renounce, and, in your sights,
Shake patiently my great affliction off:
=-=-=

Back to the Sonnet.....

3. Why do you (my soul) languish within (my body,)
and suffer deprivation of what's good for you, while allowing
4. Decoration of your outward, bodily appearance, with such
lavish expense?

5. Why so much wealth, on something that
lasts such a short time,
6. Do you spend upon your decaying embodiment?

7. Shall worms, the inevitable inheritors of this excess
expenditure on the body,
8. Ultimately consume your bodily forces, and the cost of them?
Is this the body's end?  [The answer is "yes."]

9. Since this must be the case, my soul, nourish yourself
by depriving your servant, the body,
10. And let the body languish, to increase your own merits;

11. "Purchase" time for divinity by "selling" hours
of worldly wastefulness;
12. "Feast" within, and don't worry about an external
show of wealth, for the body.

13.     Thusly, my soul, you will prey on Death, that
feeds on men,
14.     And by "consuming" Death, you'll gain eternal life.
=======

In this Sonnet, the Poet's hopes turn from the natural world to his
prospects for the hereafter.  As Gary mentions, there's no sign of
Fair Youth or Dark Lady this time; the Poet's attention is on
himself.  It is probably a late Sonnet, since thoughts of death loom
larger as one ages.  The compositor was probably correct to position
this Sonnet near the end of the series.  The theme places it late in
the Poet's career.

The "Painting" idea, line 4, also tends to go along with aging, as in
the use of makeup by women to conceal skin effects of aging.
"Painting" is a prominent theme of Hamlet, and also mentioned
elsewhere by the Poet.  He was against "painting," apparently from
seeing so much of it, so misused.

The Poet adjures his soul to pay less heed to things of the body, and
attend more to spiritual health.  As Robert says, the specifics are
not given, but it's likely the Poet refers to simpler diet and
clothing, and a humble lifestyle in general.  It's traditional, and
classical, that religious health is gained by abstinence from the
luxuries of the world, and by limiting even the necessities.

I do not see the relationship within the Sonnet that Walton Litz
proposed, mentioned by Robert.  The "feeding" concept enters at line
8, clearly enough, but introducing it as a judgment call at line 2
only begs the question.  There is also the elementary point that the
body is not, in fact, fed by the soul, rather, the body is fed by the
foodstuff of the world, the fruits of the earth.  So I reject that,
and take it that the Poet is calling upon his soul to renounce the
things of the body, as I mention above, and with some support from the
Lear quote, at least, which provides a case of association between
"world" and "renounce" in the Poet's writings.
