The theory that this was an accident
requires us to believe that there was no
checking or copy-proofing whatever --
not by the printer, nor anyone else in the
print shop, and certainly not by the poet,
nor anyone associated with him, nor by
any publisher (whether honest or piratical).
Errors of this dimension are unknown in
both modern and Elizabethan texts.  Were
one to occur, the whole book would be
rejected -- then as much as today -- and
the printer would be told to do the whole
thing again.

Printing was very much slower and more
expensive then, while checking was no
different.  In this case, one does not have to
know the language, nor read the text, to see
the 'problem'.  Line 2 in its printed form is
much longer than it 'should' be -- much longer
than all the other lines in the Sonnet, and
much longer than any others on the page.
It stands like the proverbial sore thumb.
The 'error' is so huge that it could not
possibly have been missed.

As most here probably know, the printing
process involved the setting out of the type
for sixteen pages at a time -- with about 40
sonnets.  A print run for the required number
of copies (250?) was then made.  The print
blocks were then broken up and the next
sixteen pages set.   Proof-readings would
have been done on the first copy to come
off the printing block, but even the most
cursory would pick up an error of the size
posited here.  If the error was not found at
this point, but later, the minimum amount of
work for the printer, would be the resetting
of those sixteen pages and the reprinting of
that run.  The amount of effort a printer
would put into checking would bear a close
relationship to the cost of fixing mistakes.

The traditional case has long been that the
Sonnets were very badly printed -- far worse
than almost any other texts of the day.  Yet
there are no typos of the usual sort, such as
where 'and' is printed as 'adn', or 'the' comes
out as 'teh', or or the same word is is repeated
(like the two last 'or's and 'is's).  The case for
'bad printing' cannot withstand inspection.

1.   Poore soule the center of my sinfull earth,
2.   My sinfull earth these rebbell powres that thee array,
3.   Why dost thou pine within and suffer dearth
4.   Painting thy outward walls so costlie gay?

So why is 'my sinfull earth' repeated?
Clearly in line 2 it is meant to stand in for
a two-syllable word, probably a verb
ending in '-ing'.

What verb, ending in '-ing', would the
poet want to use, but feel unable to put
into print?  It is also probably something
to do with 'sinfull', 'center' and 'earth'.

Tough, eh?

Paul.
