screaming and insults back and forth (not by Robert and Gary, of
course). But I do still read the sonnet threads.

I was thinking about this sonnet. It seems to me that as well as
addressing his soul, Shakespeare could be addressing another person.
Perhaps the fair youth, whose beauty is fading?

This sonnet does seems to me to link up in a way with the fair youth
sonnets, particularly the marriage sonnets. The language of the pleas
to get an heir are somewhat echoed in

Shall wormes inheritors of this excesse
Eate vp thy charge? is this thy bodies end?
Then soule liue thou vpon thy seruants losse,
And let that pine to aggrauat thy store...

although the message is undeniably different. Instead of "Stop wasting
your life, and get an heir before you die," it's more "Stop wasting
your life and make something worthwhile of yourself before you die."

It also seems a kind of antithesis of Sonnet 18, and brought me back
to it with the "having so short a lease" half line. Perhaps this is
the same addressee grown older, and the sonnet is out of place. I
believe it may belong at the very end of the fair youth suite. But I
disagree that it comes out of nowhere.

Best wishes,
