Not necessarily. In fact I would suggest that the atheism
indicated by 125 - being far more strongly supported by
religious references than this one is - means that we need
to question whether the almost universal assumption that
this is a 'Christian' sonnet is actually correct.

You say that this doesn't seem to have anything to do with
the Dark Lady, but why not? No fewer than 17 of the 25
surrounding sonnets are apparently addressed to her, and
the other 8 (with the possible exceptions of 129 &amp; 145)
almost certainly about her. At least the first two quat-
rains of this one could just as easily have been addressed
to her.

1. Poore soule the center of my sinfull earth,

'Poor soul' as a form of address is used throughout the
canon in reference to a *person* (or in one case a lamb)
who for some reason is to be pitied.

Poor soul, God's goodness hath been great to thee.
(Simpcox)

Go, go, poor soul. I envy not thy glory.
(Lady Anne)

Poor soul, thy face is much abused with tears.
(Juliet)

Alack, poor soul, thou hast need of more rags to
lay on thee rather than have these off.
(Autolycus)

It is also worth noting that only a few sonnets earlier
he had been writing about her in terms of his 'sin', so
he might well describe her as the centre of his 'sinful
earth':

Only my plague thus far I count my gain:
That she that makes me sin awards me pain.
(141)

Love is my sin, and thy dear virtue hate,
Hate of my sin grounded on sinful loving.
(142)

Grounded?

It may also relate to Sonnet 144's idea of the "female
evil", suggesting perhaps that the "better angel" is the
centre of his purer world. A central theme of the whole
Sonnet is dying, of course, so we should perhaps also
note the phrase "thys synneful worlde" in the 1559
Burial Service.

2. (...) these rebbell powres that thee array,

Robert's 'feeding' is as good a guess as any. When we
discussed this on SHAKSPER recently, I suggested
"sieged by", but I now think that "feeding" is more
likely. My amendment of Paul's idea to "****ed by" is
quite appealing though!

The "rebbell powres" that "array" her I would take
mainly to be the physical signs of ageing which are
afflicting or even disfiguring her. The OED actually
quotes "Indeed age hath arrayed thee!" as an example
of the latter.

3. Why dost thou pine within and suffer dearth
4. Painting thy outward walls so costlie gay?

Why do you let your mind go hungry, while spending so
much on decorating and renovating your physical self?

5. Why so large cost hauing so short a lease,
6. Dost thou vpon thy fading mansion spend?

Why spend so much time and money on your disinteg-
rating body, given that you have possession of it
for so short a time?

7. Shall wormes inheritors of this excesse
8. Eate vp thy charge? is this thy bodies end?

I can't do any better than Robert on this: "Are the
worms which will get all this in the end to feed at
your expense? Is that what your body is for?"
I certainly like the idea of "end" being about its
purpose as well as its termination.

9. Then soule liue thou vpon thy seruants losse,
10. And let that pine to aggrauat thy store;

I think that at this point the meaning of 'soul' does
change from the person alone to something which more
addresses the intellectual or spiritual power *within*
that person (see Stonehouse's Law of Changed Meanings).
They should spend more time and effort on developing
this than on saving their looks. 'Spiritual' need not
mean 'religious', of course.

11. Buy tearmes diuine in selling houres of drosse:

Shakespeare uses the words "term" or "terms" as nouns
some 85 times, and about two thirds of the time he
means words or expressions, such as in:

With many holiday and lady terms
He questioned me;

The other third mainly concern conditions of some
kind:

'Tis not well
That you and I should meet upon such terms
As now we meet.

But just a few are about *limited* spans of time:

I am thy father's spirit,
Doomed for a certain term to walk the night,

and I found only one of these in the plural, refer-
ring to the legal year:

...the wearing out of six fashions - which is
four terms, or two actions

Given the comparison with "hours", I nevertheless
think that it must be lengths of time he is talking
about here. However, I certainly can't see this as
having anything to do with eternity, which is by
definition *unlimited*.

"Divine" need not have a religious meaning either.
The OED (5.b) gives "Of things: Of surpassing beauty,
perfection, excellence, etc.; extraordinarily good
or great." and quotes *Romeo and Juliet*:

Dove-feathered raven, wolvish-ravening lamb!
Despised substance of divinest show!

So, "swap the recrementitious hours you waste (in
titivating your body) for times of surpassing beauty
(in developing your mind)" - or something like that?

12. Within be fed, without be rich no more,

Wise up mind-wise (and body-wise likewise?).

13. So shalt thou feed on death,that feeds on men,
14. And death once dead,ther's no more dying then.

There can be little doubt that the poet had the words
of the burial service in the back of his mind: "The
laste enemye that shalbe destroyed is deathe". On the
other hand, I can't help being reminded of the Bishop
of Carlisle's words in *Richard II* in which we find,
surprisingly for a bishop, little if any 'religion':

To fear the foe, since fear oppresseth strength,
Gives in your weakness strength unto your foe;
And so your follies fight against yourself.
Fear, and be slain. No worse can come to fight;
And fight and die is death destroying death,
Where fearing dying pays death servile breath.

Peter G. has also reminded us a couple of times at
least of the (Friar) Duke's rather pagan advice to
Claudio about facing death. (MfM 5.1.5-41)

In the sonnet, is he similarly saying that it is the
*fear* of dying (as represented by her concentration
on the "fading mansion") that can be minimized by
changing to being "fed within"? And once she is
*really* dead, the process of dying - and suffering -
stops anyway.

Peter F.
