Does this interpretation of particular phrases add up to a
coherent version of the argument of the poem? In the early
days (1996?) I held out for some time against doing an
interlinear paraphrase because it seemed to disguise the
continuity of the overall argument. I am still convinced
that the first thing to do (not the last thing, and not a
particularly elevated thing) is to grasp the argument as a
whole. Following that, we can go on to other things, but
without it we are merely bombinating in a vacuum.

On the other hand, it would be hard to write a religious
poem without referring to sin. Most of these other words are
very common ones. A lot of common words can be taken in
special ways - I see I have just written about an 'elevated
thing', and what could prurient imagination make of that?
But this sonnet reads to me like a perfectly serious
discussion of a religious point, coming in a group of unique
sonnets because Shakespeare has decided to have such a group
in his book - not just out of nowhere.

