1.   Poore soule the center of my sinfull earth,
2.   My sinfull earth these rebbell powres that thee array,
3.   Why dost thou pine within and suffer dearth
4.   Painting thy outward walls so costlie gay?
5.   Why so large cost hauing so short a lease,
6.   Dost thou vpon thy fading mansion spend?
7.   Shall wormes inheritors of this excesse,
8.   Eate vp thy charge? is this thy bodies end?
9.   Then soule liue thou vpon thy seruants losse,
10.   And let that pine to aggrauat thy store;
11.   Buy tearmes diuine in selling houres of drosse:
12.   Within be fed, without be rich no more,
13.     So shalt thou feed on death, that feeds on men,
14.     And death once dead, ther's no more dying then.

This sonnet is an attack on Raleigh and is
largely 'addressed' to him.  The poet leaves
hints that another addressee is the Queen
herself, in that while all of what he says is
meant for Raleigh, much of it also fits her.
She was meant to read it, thinking she was
intended, but eventually working out its
real target was Raleigh.

The superficial religious theme of the 'body /
soul' opposition is maintained -- but without
IMHO a great deal of interest.

1.   Poore soule the center of my sinfull earth,

Oxford's tone is mockingly pitying. It is a
sarcastic comment upon Raleigh's poetic
style (and probably also on his spoken
manner) with his endless moans about the
state of the world and the corruption of the
court while, in reality, Raleigh was raking in
huge sums.

The 'soul' in these sonnets is usually Raleigh,
as in 'the prophetic soul of the wide world' of
Sonnet 107.  He liked to discuss the concept
of 'the soul', getting into some minor legal
trouble for it in 1594 with a couple of zealous,
if obtuse, clergymen.  He sought to save the
Queen's sole with his cloak in that famous
escapade.  Her first gift of leases to him played
on the conceit, being the property of All Souls
College in Oxford.

2.   My sinfull earth these rebbell powres that thee array,
2.   [Fucked by] these rebbell powres that thee array,

The duplication of 'my sinfull earth' in the
Quarto is so conspicuous and so egregious
a 'mistake' that it can only be deliberate.  In
the form as printed, it causes the line to be
much longer than all others on the page.
See:

http://extra.shu.ac.uk/emls/Sonnets/i3r.jpg

An error of that size could never get past a
remotely competent printer or proof-reader.
We have seen several 'mistakes' of this sort
in the Sonnets before -- such as when the
poet intends to convey 'shite', he gives us a
false rhyme;  in Sonnet 25: 'quite' to 'worth',
and in Sonnet 144: 'sight' to 'pride'.

We still have to guess exactly what the poet
intended;  I first thought the missing syllables
were 'Fucking' -- partly as the common expletive,
and partly because it seems to tie in well with
" . . the center of 'my sinfull earth '.   However,
Peter Farey suggests 'Fucked by', which
provides a much better meter.

'Those rebbell powres' were primarily the Irish
in Munster, against whom Raleigh fought in
1579-80, with some success, but who still
dominated much of Munster and continued
to cause trouble to his extensive estates.

3.   Why dost thou pine within and suffer dearth

Raleigh had to extensively refurbish Durham
House to make it habitable, and to provide
Hariot with his observatory under the roof.
In doing all this he was 'pining within'.

'Dearth' is etymologically related to 'dear' and
was used in its older sense by Shake-speare.
Here he plays on both senses. All could see
the vast sums Raleigh was pouring into
Durham House (and into his other enterprises),
yet he was forever complaining of shortage of
funds.

'Dearth' (OED)
2. Dearness, costliness, high price. Obsolete.
1596 Bp. Barlow Three Serm. i. 5 Dearth is that, when all those things which belong
to the life of man . . . are rated at a high price.]
1632 in Cramond Ann. Banff (1891) I. 67 Compleining of . . . the dearthe of the pryce
thairof.
1644 R. Baillie Lett. &amp; Jrnls. (1841) II. 175, I cannot help the extraordinarie dearth:
they say the great soume the author putts on his copie, is the cause of it.
1602 Shakes. Ham. v. ii. 123 His infusion of such dearth and rareness.

4.   Painting thy outward walls so costlie gay?

The huge riverside walls of Durham House
would have been repainted.  Our poet finds the
colour garish. Of course, he is also referring to
Raleigh's dress.

5.   Why so large cost hauing so short a lease,

Raleigh was merely allowed by the Queen to
reside at Durham House.  There was no 'lease'
and our poet is being sarcastic.  He is saying
that Raleigh's time as favourite will be very
short.

6.   Dost thou vpon thy fading mansion spend?

There is undoubtedly a play on 'fading man
scion'; ('sion' was a common spelling at the
time;  the same wordplay occurs in Sonnet 95
in a similar context),   This would seem to
indicate 1581 as the date of composition.

Durham House was exceedingly dilapidated,
and Raleigh's refurbishments could not rectify
its huge structural problems.

'Fading' is also being used in a sense employed
about Autocylus (a caricature of Raleigh) in
*Winters Tale*.

'Fading' (OED)
The name of a dance, app. Irish. 'With a fading' was the refrain of a popular
song of an indecent character.
1611 Beaum. &amp; Fl. Knt. Burning Pestle iii. v, I will have him dance Fading;
Fading is a fine jig.
1611 Shakes. Wint. T. iv. iv. 195 He has the prettiest Loue-songs . . . with
such delicate burthens of Dildo's and Fadings.

7.   Shall wormes inheritors of this excesse,

Our poet identifies the lower-classes as 'worms'.
Also, it seems, he intends Puritans -- no doubt
partly from an allusion to the Diet of Worms.
He says that they will soon acquire all this
wealth and these fine palaces -- insofar as
anything will be left after the civil war over the
succession.

8.   Eate vp thy charge? is this thy bodies end?

Raleigh was made 'Esquire of  the Body Extra-
ordinary' in 1581 -- a lowly rank which did not
reflect the extent of the Queen's favour.  His
'charge' was the person of the Queen.  The
'worms' (of all sorts) will destroy everything
of value, since she has made no provision for
continuity.  'Thy body' in this context is that
of the Queen.

The tone sounds as though the poet hopes
for the marriage of the Queen, but other factors,
such as Raleigh's accumulation of wealth, seem
to date the sonnet to 1583-4.  It's quite possible
that the later date apples and our poet is merely
continuing to speak in his Cassandra voice saying
"I was right . . . I told you so" lamenting the end
of the Tudor dynasty and foretelling catastrophe.

