Robert's question was directed at Lynne
and he expects the answer 'No' -- which
is fair enough considering the haphazard
and vague nature of her suggestions.

However, he is implicitly setting it against
his own account, which MIGHT be said
to provide a 'coherent version of the
argument'.  But it has huge deficiencies,
the most obvious being that it is banal in
the extreme.  Robert implicitly (if not
explicitly) rejects any taint of ambiguity.
For a start, its presence would obscure
and impede his 'coherent version'.
He could be said to represent an ancient
tradition of 'Sonnet interpretation', which
is still, in effect, the dominant model.
The pupil asks of a poem "What does it
mean?" and the teacher explains in one
simple theme.

However, the more intelligent of modern
commentators no longer expect to provide
simple answers to simple questions, and
vague as Lynne's ideas are, she is at least
working along the right lines.  Any remotely
satisfactory answer _must_ be complicated.

Paul.
