Someone remarked to Philip Larkin how hard it must be to get
everything into rhyme and metre. He said no, that was the
easy part: the really hard part was having something to say
in the first place. (I think this is in his letters, but
have hunted for ages without finding it again.)

I have the strong (subjective) impression that Shakespeare
was doing just the same thing, which very few poets in the
intervening four hundred years have understood. Each poem is
meant to say some thing which it is up to us to grasp. That
supports the impression I have from the sonnets themselves
that there is a coherent argument in each poem and it
matters.

Now, I agree about the kaleidoscope. But, if there were no
solid, fundamental framework, the kaleidoscopic effects
would be a mere house of cards, crumbling at a touch. So
these are two levels I see in the sonnets - goodness knows
what the total number of levels is.

