I can't claim 'must'! The impression I get, though, is of
the soul under attack, being eaten away, from outside. So
coming across the 'rebel powers' in the second line, I
looked for a public meaning that would be generally
accessible to someone who had not yet read further. The
expression 'rebel powers' was familiar, but admittedly from
Milton who was not around yet.

I accept that the rebel powers could be the tendencies
leading to sin (hence 'sinful') of the individual himself.
The sinful earth which clothes (arrays) the central soul
also eats it away.(So there is also a change in the meaning
of 'array'.)  In fact, I rather like this - it avoids
bringing in the devils from hell, who seem to have no other
function in the poem.

Plato was saying something rather similar, though I wouldn't
suggest Shakespeare got it from him.

So the revised paraphrase is:

My persecuted soul, living in the middle of my body which is
made of clay and filled with sin,
providing nourishment for these sinful elements that clothe
you,
why do you go hungry in there, enduring famine
to decorate the outer body with such expensive ornaments?
Why so much, when your tenancy is so short,
do you spend to restore your crumbling building?
Are the worms which will get all this in the end
to feed at your expense? Is that what your body is for?
Soul, you should take from the body for your own sustenance,
let the body go short to increase your spiritual wealth,
sell off short-lived valueless stuff in exchange for God's
immortality,
take inward nourishment and give up the outward appearances
of wealth.
By doing that, you will tear apart death, which tears men
apart,
and when death is destroyed, you have no more danger of
dying.

--
Robert Stonehouse
